'''Bradley Charles Cooper'''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bradley Cooper Webchat Transcript|url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1217|publisher=Empire Online|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> (born January 5, 1975)<ref name=filmref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/16/Bradley-Cooper.html|title=Bradley Cooper biodata|publisher=FilmReference.com|accessdate=December 2, 2014}}</ref> is an American actor and producer. He has been nominated for four [[Academy Awards]], three for acting and one for producing. He was named the "[[Sexiest Man Alive]]" by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradley Cooper Is ''People''{{'}}s Sexiest Man Alive!|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/article/0,,20315920_20545580,00.html|work=People|accessdate=November 18, 2011|first=Alexis|last=Chiu|first2=Charlotte|last2=Triggs|date=November 16, 2011}}</ref>

Cooper has a [[B.A.]] in English from [[Georgetown University]] (1997) and an [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in acting from [[Actors Studio Drama School]] at [[The New School]] (2000). He first gained recognition in the spy-action television show ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'' and the television drama ''[[Jack & Bobby]]''. He later appeared in supporting roles in the romantic comedies ''[[Wedding Crashers]]'' (2005), ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]'' (2008), and ''[[He's Just Not That Into You (film)|He's Just Not That Into You]]'' (2009). His breakthrough role came with the comedy franchise [[The Hangover (franchise)|''The Hangover'' trilogy]] (2009<U+2013>13). Other notable films include the action-comedy ''[[The A-Team (film)|The A-Team]]'' (2010), the thriller ''[[Limitless]]'' (2011), the crime drama ''[[The Place Beyond the Pines]]'' (2013), and the superhero film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' (2014), in which he had a voice role.

Cooper garnered three consecutive Oscar nominations for his roles in the romantic comedy ''[[Silver Linings Playbook]]'' (2012), the comedy-drama ''[[American Hustle]]'' (2013), and the biographical war drama ''[[American Sniper (film)|American Sniper]]'' (2014). For producing ''American Sniper'', Cooper also received an [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] nomination.

==Early life==
Cooper was born in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]<ref name=filmref/> and grew up nearby in [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania|Jenkintown]]<ref name="GQ"/><ref name=jenkintown/> and [[Rydal, Pennsylvania|Rydal]].<ref name="nyt2011">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/movies/bradley-cooper-in-the-hangover-part-ii-and-limitless.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Don<U+2019>t Take This Hunk at Face Value |publisher=''The New York Times'' |date=March 10, 2011 |first=Jonah |last=Weiner |accessdate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref> His mother, Gloria (n<U+00E9>e Campano),<ref>http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2011/03/18/Bradley-Cooper-s-the-lead-his-idol-s-the-co-star/stories/201103180183</ref><ref name=charles-obit>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/philly/obituary.aspx?n=charles-j-cooper&pid=147904836#fbLoggedOut|title=Charles J. Cooper obituary at|publisher=Legacy.com|date=January 15, 2011|accessdate=April 19, 2013}}</ref> worked for the local [[NBC]] affiliate.<ref name="GQ">{{cite web|last=Baron|first=Zach|title=The GQ Cover Story: Bradley Cooper Is A-List Now, Bro|url=http://www.gq.com/entertainment/celebrities/201401/bradley-cooper-cover-story-january-2014|work=[[GQ]]|date=January 2014}}</ref> His father, Charles Cooper, who died January 15, 2011, worked as a stockbroker for [[Merrill Lynch]].<ref name=metro-uk>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/11/19/bradley-cooper-daniel-day-lewis-told-me-he-liked-the-hangover-501100|title=Bradley Cooper: Daniel Day-Lewis told me he liked 'The Hangover'|first=Lesley|last=O'Toole|date=November 19, 2012|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|location=UK|accessdate= December 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/9691230/Post-Hangover-bliss-Bradley-Cooper-interview.html|title=Post-Hangover bliss: Bradley Cooper interview|first=Vicki|last=Reid|date=Nov 23, 2012|accessdate=December 2, 2014|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|location=UK}}</ref> He has an older sister, Holly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/200905/bradley-cooper-from-wedding-crashers-talks-the-hangover|title=Bradley Cooper Is High on the Hangover|work=Details.com|first=Kevin|last=Conley|accessdate=July 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Cooper-Dad-Dies-1028058.aspx|title=Bradley Cooper's Dad Dies|author=Joyce Eng|work=TVGuide}}</ref><ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2011</ref> He was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theinsider.com/news/2820023_Bradley_Cooper_Says_He_Is_An_Old_Romantic|title=Bradley Cooper Says He Is An Old Romantic |publisher=The Insider|date=September 7, 2009|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> His father was of [[Irish people|Irish]] descent and his mother is of Italian ancestry.<ref name=metro-uk/><ref>{{cite web|last=Bouys|first=Gabriel|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/bradley-cooper-im-a-romantic-200949|title=Bradley Cooper: I'm a "Romantic" |work=[[Us Weekly]]|quote=I grew up in a very old-fashioned Roman Catholic, Italian-Irish family in Philly.|date=September 4, 2009|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> Cooper had [[cholesteatoma]] in his ear soon after his birth and punctured it when he started diving at a young age.<ref name="thr2012"/> His childhood friend was actor [[Brian Klugman]].<ref name="nyt2011"/> While attending [[Germantown Academy]], Cooper worked at the ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]''.<ref name=jenkintown>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/dailynews/features/20090526_Hangin__with_Mr__Cooper__Jenkintown_native_Bradley_Cooper_stars_in_the_hilariously_dirty__quot_The_Hangover_quot_.html|archiveurl=//web.archive.org/web/20090529034025/http://www.philly.com/dailynews/features/20090526_Hangin__with_Mr__Cooper__Jenkintown_native_Bradley_Cooper_stars_in_the_hilariously_dirty__quot_The_Hangover_quot_.html|archivedate=May 29, 2009|title=Hangin' with Mr. Cooper: Jenkintown native Bradley Cooper stars in the hilariously dirty "The Hangover"|work=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|last=Gross|first=Dan|date=May 26, 2009|accessdate=May 29, 2009}}</ref>

After graduating from Germantown Academy in 1993,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/phillygossip/Germantown_Academy_grad_Bradley_Cooper_talks_about_The_Hangover.html|title=Germantown Academy grad Bradley Cooper talks about ''The Hangover''|publisher=Philly.com|date=May 26, 2009|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> Cooper attended [[Villanova University]] for one year, then later transferred to [[Georgetown University]], from which he graduated with honors with a [[Bachelor of Arts#United States|BA]] in English in 1997.<ref name="about">{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/od/cooperbradley/p/bradley-cooper.htm|title=Bradley Cooper Biography|work=About.com|first=Rebecca|last=Murray|accessdate=May 25, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgetown.edu/story/1242664588541.html|publisher=[[Georgetown University]]|date=September 3, 2010|accessdate=September 9, 2011|title=Bradley Cooper Comes Back to Georgetown}}</ref> He was a member of the [[Georgetown Hoyas]] rowing team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hemispheresmagazine.com/2011/03/01/hemi-qa-bradley-cooper/ |title=Hemi Q&A: Bradley Cooper |publisher=Hemispheres Magazine |date=March 1, 2011 |first=David |last=Carr |accessdate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/features/bradley-cooper-interview-0611-4 |title=Dinner with Bradley |publisher=''Esquire'' |date=June 9, 2011 |first=Lisa |last=Taddeo |accessdate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/bradley-cooper-interview |title=BRADLEY COOPER INTERVIEW |publisher=Shortlist.com |date=2011 |accessdate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref> and acted with [[Nomadic Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.georgetownvoice.com/2010/09/03/bradley-cooper-speaks-in-gaston-campus-population-swoons/ |title=Bradley Cooper speaks in Gaston, campus population swoons |publisher=Georgetown Voice |date=September 3, 2010 |accessdate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref>

Cooper became fluent in French at Georgetown and spent six months as an exchange student in [[Aix-en-Provence]], France.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Lori|url=http://www.denverpost.com/entertainment/ci_18191068|title=People: Taylor and Burton's Brangelina romance to be a film|work=The Denver Post |date=September 14, 2010|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zuckerman|first=Esther|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20286689,00.html|title=Five Things You Need to Know About Bradley Cooper|work=People|date=June 22, 2009 |accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://videos.tf1.fr/jt-20h/bradley-cooper-la-coqueluche-de-hollywood-sur-le-plateau-de-tf1-6510828.html|title=Le journal de 20h|date=May 30, 2011|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> Later in 2000, he received an [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in acting from [[Actors Studio Drama School]] at [[The New School]] (now the [[Actors Studio Drama School at Pace University]]) in New York City.<ref name="about"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschool.edu/alumni/news-notes/news/drama.aspx|title=Alumni News|date=May 2010|publisher=The New School|accessdate=August 28, 2011|archiveurl=//web.archive.org/web/20110811203128/http://www.newschool.edu/alumni/news-notes/news/drama.aspx|archivedate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> While studying at [[The New School]], Cooper worked as a doorman at the [[Morgans Hotel]].<ref name="GQ"/>

==Career==
===Late 1990s-2004===
Cooper began his professional acting career with a small guest role in one episode of the television show ''[[Sex and the City]]'' in 1999<ref name=tca/> and served as a presenter in the travel-adventure series ''[[Globe Trekker]]''. After his film debut in the satirical comedy ''[[Wet Hot American Summer]]'', which later garnered a cult following, Cooper played [[Will Tippin]] in [[J.J. Abrams]]' successful television spy-action drama ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]''<ref name=tca/> and acted in the 2002 psychological thriller ''[[Changing Lanes]]''. The scenes in which he appeared were edited out of the final cut of the film, but are featured on the film's DVD and Blu-ray releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/693650?view=cast |title=BFI Film & TV Database: ''Changing Lanes'' 2002 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=August 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/changing-lanes/9 |title=''Changing Lanes'' DVD Review |last=Gonzalez |first=Ed |work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=August 27, 2002 |accessdate=August 28, 2011}}</ref> After leaving ''Alias'' in 2003, Cooper guest-starred on the short-lived TV series ''[[Miss Match]]'' and later returned twice to ''Alias'' to reprise his role in guest appearances.

Cooper played the part of cowboy and race horse trainer Morgan Murphy in the TV movie ''The Last Cowboy'', which aired on the [[Hallmark Channel]] in January, 2003. He also co-starred in the [[ABC Family]] film ''[[I Want to Marry Ryan Banks]]'' with [[Jason Priestley]], and appeared as a regular guest star in the [[WB Television Network|WB]] series ''[[Jack & Bobby]]''. He played the popular villain Sack Lodge in the hit comedy ''[[Wedding Crashers]]'' and appeared in the film ''[[Failure to Launch]]'' as Demo, a friend of Tripp ([[Matthew McConaughey]]). 
[[File:Bradley Cooper 2009.jpg|thumb|upright|Cooper at the 2009 [[Tribeca Film Festival]] premiere of [[Woody Allen]]'s film, ''[[Whatever Works]]'' in April 2009.]]

===2005-2010===
In September 2005, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] debuted the sitcom ''[[Kitchen Confidential (TV series)|Kitchen Confidential]]'', based on a memoir by chef [[Anthony Bourdain]], with Cooper in the leading role. Despite positive reviews for the series, the show was canceled after four episodes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Adalian |first=Josef |title='OC' sees new slot amid Fox sked shakeup|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117935016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 21, 2005 |page=3|accessdate=January 31, 2012 | quote = Fox also quietly benched critically hailed frosh laffer ''Kitchen Confidential'' last week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Adalian |first=Josef |title=Alphabet has Star quality|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117935067|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 21, 2005 |page=1|accessdate=January 31, 2012}}</ref> In March 2006, he starred in ''[[Three Days of Rain]]'' on Broadway with [[Julia Roberts]] and [[Paul Rudd]] at the Bernard B. Jacobs Theater.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brantley |first=Ben |title=It's Her! It's Her! And, Oh Yeah, There's a Play |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 20, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Paul_Rudd_and_Bradley_Cooper_Round_out_Three_Days_of_Rain_Cast_with_Julia_Roberts_Show_Begins_March_28_20051129|title=Paul Rudd and Bradley Cooper Round out Three Days of Rain Cast with Julia Roberts, Show Begins March 28|work=Broadway World.com|date=November 29, 2005|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> He also appeared on stage as Jake in the 2008 production of [[Theresa Rebeck]]'s play ''The Understudy'' at the [[Williamstown Theatre Festival]] alongside [[Kristen Johnston]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/theater_arts/articles/2008/07/29/the_understudy_combines_comedy_and_kafka_in_williamstown/ |title={{-'}}The Understudy' combines comedy and Kafka in Williamstown|last=Kennedy |first=Louise |date=July 28, 2008 |accessdate=August 29, 2011| work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Cooper appeared in Season 5 of ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' (2007) as Aidan Stone, a television star on the fictional show ''Hearts 'N Scalpels''. In 2008, Cooper had roles in ''[[Yes Man (film)|Yes Man]]'' with [[Jim Carrey]] and in ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]'' with [[Rainn Wilson]]. On February 7, 2009, Cooper hosted ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' with musical guest [[TV on the Radio]].  In one skit, Cooper portrayed actor [[Christian Bale]] as spokesperson for a DVD called, "No, Bruce! Let Me Finish! The Best of Celebrity Tirades."

In 2009, Cooper starred in the films ''[[He's Just Not That Into You (film)|He's Just Not That Into You]]'', ''[[Case 39]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20297504,00.html |title=Bradley, Ren<U+00E9>e Get Cozy in Barcelona |work=People |date=August 12, 2009 |accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> ''[[All About Steve (film)|All About Steve]]'' and ''[[The Hangover (film)|The Hangover]]'', which was wildly successful. Cooper's role as [[Phil Wenneck]] in ''The Hangover'' is perhaps the role for which he is best known. The film first opened in the United States and went on to gross over $467 million worldwide. Its production budget was $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hangover.htm|title=The Hangover (2009)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=January 8, 2013}}</ref> Following ''The Hangover'', the premiere of ''All About Steve'' was met with mostly negative reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/all_about_steve[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|title=All About Steve|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref> Cooper's performance, along with co-star Sandra Bullock, was poorly received by critics and, despite his recent success with ''[[The Hangover (film)|The Hangover]]'', the film only saw mild success at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=allaboutsteve.htm[[Box Office Mojo]]|title=All About Steve|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>  Although the success of ''The Hangover'' brought Cooper new opportunities, Cooper stated in a 2011 interview with [[Shave (magazine)|Shave Magazine]], "It<U+2019>s the same. I mean, look, more doors have been opened for sure, but it<U+2019>s not like I sit back with a cigar on Monday morning and go through the scripts that have been offered."<ref name="shavemagazine">{{cite web |url=http://www.shavemagazine.com/entertainment/Interview-Bradley-Cooper |title=Interview: Bradley Cooper |publisher=ShaveMagazine.com |first=Rameez |last=Karim |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref>
[[File:Bradley Cooper, July 2009 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Cooper, in 2009 during a United Service Organizations tour.]]
In October 2009, Cooper received the Hollywood Comedy Award at the 13th Annual [[Hollywood Film Festival|Hollywood Film Festival and Hollywood Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodfest.com/2009/10/hollywood-fest-honors-julianne-moore|title=Hollywood Fest Honors Julianne Moore|publisher=Hollywood Film Festival|date=October 10, 2009|accessdate=August 28, 2011}}</ref> and later that year, he and Sandra Bullock were nominated for a Razzie Award for their roles in ''[[All About Steve (film)|All About Steve]]'', which they went on to win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.razzies.com/history/09winners.asp|work=[[Razzie Awards]]|title=30th Annual Golden Raspberry ("Razzie") Award "Winners"|publisher=[[Razzie Awards]]|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>In 2010, Cooper appeared in the ensemble romantic comedy ''[[Valentine's Day (2010 film)|Valentine's Day]]'', directed by [[Garry Marshall]], which also starred [[Ashton Kutcher]], [[Jessica Alba]], [[Jessica Biel]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Julia Roberts]] and former ''Alias'' co-star [[Jennifer Garner]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Garry Marshall Gets a Cast For Valentine's Day|url=http://www.buzzsugar.com/Garry-Marshall-Gets-Cast-Valentines-Day-3143951|work=BuzzSugar|publisher=Sugar, Inc|accessdate=January 8, 2013|date=May 12, 2009}}</ref> The film was a commercial success, grossing over $215 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=valentinesday.htm|title=Valentine's Day (2010)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=January 8, 2013}}</ref> He then played the role of [[Templeton "Faceman" Peck]] in the feature film version of ''[[The A-Team (film)|The A-Team]]''. Cooper and his ''The A-Team'' co-stars [[Sharlto Copley]] and [[Quinton Jackson]] appeared together as [[List of WWE Raw guest hosts|guest co-hosts]] of ''[[WWE Raw]]'' on June 7, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/06/07/the-a-team-hosts-wwes-first-ever-raw-viewers-choice-night/53361|title=The A-Team Hosts WWE's First Ever Raw Viewer's Choice Night|first=Bill|last=Gorman|work=TV by the Numbers|date=June 7, 2010|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref>

===2011-2015===
In 2011, Cooper starred in the techno-thriller ''[[Limitless]]'', based on the 2001 novel ''[[The Dark Fields]]'' by [[Alan Glynn]], and the comedy sequel to ''The Hangover'', ''[[The Hangover Part II]]'', which earned over $580 million at the box office worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hangover2.htm|title=The Hangover Part II (2011)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=January 8, 2013}}</ref> In September 2011, ''[[GQ]]'' UK presented Cooper with the "International Man of the Year" award<ref>{{cite news|last=Harmsworth|first=Andrei|title=U2 and Matt Smith among winners at GQ Men of the Year awards|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/874670-u2-and-matt-smith-among-winners-at-gq-men-of-the-year-awards|accessdate=March 18, 2012|newspaper=Metro|date=September 6, 2011}}</ref> and in the November 16, 2011 issue of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, Cooper was named Sexiest Man Alive.<ref>[http://www.accesshollywood.com/bradley-cooper-named-2011s-sexiest-man-alive_article_56783 "Bradley Cooper Named Sexiest Man Alive"], ''Access Hollywood'', November 16, 2011</ref>In 2012, he starred with [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Jennifer Lawrence]] in [[David O. Russell]]'s ''[[Silver Linings Playbook]]'', an adaptation of [[Matthew Quick]]'s serio-comic novel of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/david-o-russell-to-direct-the-silver-linings-playbook|title=David O. Russell to Direct The Silver Linings Playbook|accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://geektyrant.com/news/2010/12/8/anne-hathaway-to-star-in-david-o-russells-the-silver-lining.html|title=Anne Hathaway To Star in David O. Russell's The Silver Lining Playbook|accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref>  Cooper's performance in the film earned him a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]]. In 2012, he starred in the crime drama ''[[The Place Beyond the Pines]]'', as a police officer,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Bradley-Cooper-filming-at-City-Hall-1915719.php|title=Bradley Cooper filming at City Hall|location=Albany, NY|work=Times Union|date=August 12, 2011|accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref> and in the drama ''[[The Words (film)|The Words]]''.

In 2013, Cooper reprised his role as Phil Wenneck in the third and final installment of ''The Hangover'' trilogy, ''[[The Hangover Part III]]'', which was almost universally panned by critics and was most heavily criticized for its darker tone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/grown_ups_2/news/1929621/vote_for_the_2013_razzie_awards_worst_screen_combo/[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|title=Vote for the 2013 Razzie Awards Worst Screen Combo|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref> Cooper was subsequently considered as a contender for his second Razzie nomination for the fan-voted "Worst Screen Combo" award, but failed to receive a nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_hangover_part_iii/[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|title=The Hangover Part III|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>  That year Cooper also appeared in the ensemble cast of David O. Russell's dramedy ''[[American Hustle]]'' alongside Christian Bale, [[Amy Adams]], [[Jeremy Renner]], and Jennifer Lawrence. His performance as an unhinged FBI agent earned him a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. Cooper reunited with ''Silver Linings Playbook'' co-star Jennifer Lawrence for director [[Susanne Bier]]'s adaptation of [[Ron Rash]]'s period novel, ''[[Serena (2014 film)|Serena]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|last2=Brodesser-Akner|first2=Claude|title=Bradley Cooper, Jennifer Lawrence Reteam for ''Serena''|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2012/01/bradley-cooper-jennifer-lawrence-reteam-for-serena.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=January 31, 2012}}</ref>

In 2014, Cooper provided the voice of [[Rocket Raccoon]] in the [[Marvel Studios]] film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/21107/official_bradley_cooper_to_voice_rocket_raccoon_in_marvels_guardians_of_the_galaxy |title=OFFICIAL: Bradley Cooper to Voice Rocket Raccoon in Marvel<U+2019>s Guardians of the Galaxy |publisher=Marvel|date=August 30, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref> Also that year, Cooper starred in the film ''[[American Sniper (film)|American Sniper]]'', about U.S. Navy SEAL sniper [[Chris Kyle]], directed by [[Clint Eastwood]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/clint-eastwood-talks-direct-american-611186|title=Clint Eastwood in Talks to Direct 'American Sniper'|date=August 21, 2013|first=Borys|last=Kit|accessdate=October 25, 2013|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> His third Academy Award nomination (his second for Best Actor) made him the 10th person to earn acting nominations in three consecutive years.<ref>http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-bradley-cooper-becomes-10th-764070</ref> He will next star with [[Emma Stone]] and [[Rachel McAdams]] in a still-untitled [[Untitled Cameron Crowe project|film project]] directed by [[Cameron Crowe]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/10/bradley-cooper-in-talks-to-star-with-emma-stone-in-cameron-crowe-directed-pic|title=Bradley Cooper In Talks To Star With Emma Stone In Cameron Crowe-Directed Pic|publisher=Deadline|date=October 24, 2012|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref> which also features [[Bill Murray]] and [[John Krasinski]].

==Other ventures==
In March 2012, Cooper and [[Warner Bros.]] entered into a two-year [[first look deal]] for his production company, 22 & Indiana Pictures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradley Cooper pacts with Warner Bros.|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118050943|accessdate=March 3, 2012|newspaper=Variety|date=March 1, 2012|author=Dave McNary|author2=Jeff Sneider}}</ref> In 2014, Cooper formed a production company with director [[Todd Phillips]], who directed Cooper in ''[[The Hangover (film series)|The Hangover]]''. They signed a three-year first-look deal with Warner Bros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/bradley-cooper-todd-phillips-form-warner-bros-based-production-company/ |title=Bradley Cooper, Todd Phillips Merge Production Companies at Warner Bros. |publisher=''The Wrap'' |date=May 16, 2014 |first=Lucas Shaw |accessdate=January 7, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://variety.com/2014/film/news/bradley-cooper-and-todd-phillips-form-new-production-company-exclusive-1201181329/ |title=Bradley Cooper and Todd Phillips Form New Production Company (EXCLUSIVE) |publisher=''Variety'' |date=May 16, 2014 |first=Justin |last=Kroll |accessdate=January 7, 2015 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Cooper does not drink alcohol, from which he [[Teetotalism|has abstained]] since he was 29, saying that it would have "sabotaged" his life.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/cooper-booze-would-have-ruined-me-29849280.html|title=Cooper: Booze would have ruined me|date=December 18, 2013|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name="thr2012">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bradley-cooper-evolution-leading-man-the-hangover-367781 |title=Bradley Cooper: The Serious Evolution of a Leading Man|publisher=''The Hollywood Reporter''|date=September 5, 2012|first=Stephen|last=Galloway|accessdate=November 18, 2014 }}</ref> 
In 2013 Cooper said that during the early part of his career, when he was in ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'', his substance addictions and doubts about his career triggered thoughts of suicide.<ref>http://www.inquisitr.com/1065256/bradley-cooper-suicide-actor-wanted-to-kill-himself-because-of-early-career-doubt/#Qr93JmW5QWZtiqMK.99</ref><ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2525236/Bradley-Cooper-admits-early-career-doubt-drugs-want-kill-himself.html</ref><ref>http://www.dhakatribune.com/entertainment/2013/dec/20/bradley-cooper-wanted-kill-himself</ref><ref>http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2013-12-18/bradley-cooper-reveals-addiction/</ref>

Cooper married actress [[Jennifer Esposito]] in late 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20006812,00.html|title=Bradley Cooper and Jennifer Esposito Marry|first=Julie|last=Jordan|work=People|date=January 4, 2007|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> In May 2007, it was announced that Esposito had filed for divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20037538,00.html|title=Jennifer Esposito, Bradley Cooper Split|first=Emily|last=Fromm|work=People|date=May 2, 2007|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> Cooper was in a relationship with [[Ren<U+00E9>e Zellweger]] from 2009 to 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradley Cooper Talks Dating Renee Zellweger, Losing Virginity|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/16/bradley-cooper-talks-dati_n_836391.html|accessdate=July 14, 2003|work=Huffington Post|date=March 16, 2011|first=Jordan|last=Zakarin}}</ref> He dated [[Zoe Saldana]] from December 2011 to January 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|date=September 25, 2012|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/bradley-cooper-zoe-saldana-dating-again-2012259|title=Bradley Cooper, Zoe Saldana Dating Again!|newspaper=USMagazine.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=January 3, 2013|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20661141,00.html|title=Buzz:Bradley Cooper & Zoe Saldana Split Again|newspaper=People.com}}</ref> He has been dating model [[Suki Waterhouse]] since March 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monde|first=Chiderah|title=SAG Awards 2014: Bradley Cooper brings girlfriend Suki Waterhouse as date|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/bradley-cooper-suki-waterhouse-show-pda-sag-awards-article-1.1584619|publisher=NY Daily News|accessdate=January 20, 2014|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Leon|first=Anya|title=PHOTO: Bradley Cooper and Suki Waterhouse Get Cozy at Sundance|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20777880,00.html|publisher=People|accessdate=January 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Saad|first=Nardine|title=Bradley Cooper, Suki Waterhouse step out for 'American Hustle'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-bradley-cooper-suki-waterhouse-american-hustle-ny-premiere-20131210,0,656944.story#axzz2r2RIkotn|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=January 21, 2014|date=December 11, 2013}}</ref>

